shared_text:
Robin Ghebreal shared a post to the group: I live/lived in Wharton, NJ.
June 3 at 3:03 PM ·

WPD
June 3 at 2:35 PM ·

We understand that many of our residents are experiencing hardship as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. The Wharton Borough Police Department, in conjunction with the Wharton Mayor and Council are happy to announce the ARK program, "Act of Random Kindness." A storage trailer has been set up in the parking lot of the police department, where members of the community can drop off non-perishable items. During the next week, we will be shopping, and accepting donations to assist our residents. The trailer will be open next week between the hours of 9am-3pm for Wharton residents who can use some of these goods.

We are also working on a secondary location to assist any residents of Mine Hill Twp who need assistance. This will also take a little time to stock up but will be available shortly.

We thank you all for your patience and support during these difficult times.

Please spread the kindness to assist those in need in our community.

post_text: Once again from the NJ State Museum
shared_text:
New Jersey State Museum
April 28 at 9:00 AM ·

For this week's Maker project, we're turning plastic bottles into beautiful butterflies. We've attached images of four butterflies you can use. The North American Butterfly Association- New Jersey butterfly club (naba.org) is a great site for pics and info on state’s butterflies.
Supplies:
Clear plastic bottles, rinsed and dried
Printed or drawn picture of a butterfly
Sharp scissors or knife to cut bottle (adult assistance, please!)
Tape
Sharpie or permanent marker
Paints and brushes
Glue gun
Twine or yarn for hanging

post_text:
Just an FYI: during these unprecedented times, we are still here to advocate for our families. If anyone needs assistance finding resources for food, family help or school help, please contact us. If you are looking for fun resources for your children, please reach out. We’re parents too and we may have something you didn’t think to look up.
Also, please contact us with resources you may have found. Sharing is certainly caring. And we can share in a safe way via the internet.
You may contact us here via private message and also via email our email is ptawharton@gmail.com or you can contact our president Kelly Elardo kelardo1@gmail.com. If we don’t have the resources available we can certainly point you in the right direction.
We’re all in this together.
Be safe and be well.
Your friends in the Wharton PTA

New Jersey State Museum
April 14 at 9:00 AM ·

Prepare to change simple paper into a silly Slinky Salamander project! New Jersey is home to 17 species of salamander (and 1 newt!) The largest #salamander is the endangered Eastern Tiger Salamander (Abystoma tigrinum tigrinum) that lives in the state's southernmost region.

Here is the supply list for Wednesday's project:
- 8 1/2 x 11 paper, plus more scrap
- markers
- scissors
- glue or tape

A little tip for you today....

Parents with an iPhone or iPad you actually have a scanner! If you are planning to scan any work to your teachers or teachers if you are scanning work to your students you can use the ‘Notes App’. Open a new note, press the camera button, the option to scan document will pop up. Once the document is scanned you can email it with less band with then a photo.

Robin Ghebreal shared a post to the group: I live/lived in Wharton, NJ.
February 26 at 8:48 PM ·

Robin Ghebreal
February 26 at 10:55 AM ·

The Wharton Municipal Alliance and the Wharton Police Department are holding this program to educate parents on some of the dangers their kids face. How predators can find kids through their tag locations. How kids are using fake names on apps to cyber bully. The ways kids can hide apps and photos on their phones. The apps and websites that can be really dangerous. It seems like each week we see another child go missing or a child that takes their own life most due to issues that tie directly to the internet. Please come out and see this valuable program. If you can, please share this on your page so we can help as many parents and families as possible.

post_text: Just wanted to clear something up. The "Me and My Guy Dance" (or Daddy Daughter Dance) that is happening at Duffy tomorrow night is for Duffy girls and their Dads, Grandpas, uncles or any other adult male figure in their lives. It's been brought to my attention that parents called the Duffy office concerned that their daughters are to be bringing a student "date" of their own age. That is not the case at all. The PTA is not promoting dating at this young age. Our plan was to host an event that had a lot of interest last year and we are happy to bring this to our families. Looking forward to seeing our attendees tomorrow night.

from the 8th grade parent Committee: Attention 8th grade parents! This is the announcement you’ve all been waiting for!

Countdown to the 8th grade CAR WASH and DANCE has officially begun. Please mark Wednesday, Feb. 20th on your calendar for our first parents’ meeting to discuss both events. It will be at 7pm in MacKinnon room 104.

Please bring your creative ideas for the dance, as this will be our one and only opportunity to come up with the themes the 8th grade class will choose from and vote on.

For those unable to attend the meeting, all information regarding dates, times and committees will be posted here as well.

These end of the year events truly are the ones the students look forward to the most. With your help, we can make them the most memorable!
